TomKat Ranch: Soils

In 2015 and 2016, Point Blue Conservation Science sampled soil at 41 sites across TomKat Ranch to evaluate soil productivity and nutrient concentrations.

Soil productivity indicators

We measured 3 indicators of soil productivity and water holding capacity, organic carbon content, soil bulk density, and water infiltration rates, as well as an overall score. Sites with relatively high scores in all 3 indicators may be the most productive while sites with relatively low scores may be good candidates for management actions designed to improve soil productivity. Glossary


Bulk density: An indicator of soil compaction, bulk density is measured as the weight of a soil sample divided by its volume (grams/cm3). Compacted soils have a higher bulk density, with reduced pore space for water infiltration, water retention, root growth, soil aeration, and seedling germination.


Water infiltration rate: Also an indicator of soil compaction, water infiltration rate is measured as the time required for soil to absorb water (minutes per inch of water). Compacted soils take longer to absorb water, increasing runoff and decreasing water available for local plant growth.


Organic carbon content: An indicator of soil organic matter and soil productivity, organic carbon is measured as the percent of soil volume made up by organic carbon. Productive soils have an abundant microbial community that contribute to high levels of soil organic matter, driving plant growth and improving soil stabilization and capacity for storing water.


Overall score: To combine values of all 3 soil metrics above into one overall score, we first calculated a separate percentile score for each metric (including separate scores for surface and deeper soil carbon). These percentile scores represent how relatively good or poor each point scored for each metric compared to all the other TomKat soil sampling points, and they were based on fitting empirical cumulative distribution functions to each metric. We then calculated an overall percentile score as the mean of these individual percentile scores, so that points with a combination of high and low scores might fall in the moderate category.

About this page

This interactive web page was produced using RStudio with the packages leaflet for mapping and DT for data tables. RStudio is a free and open-source software for programming in R, a programming language for statistical computing and graphics. The code used to produce this web page is available on Github.
